com.conceptwave.scripting
Class ResourceCache

com.conceptwave.scripting.Object
  com.conceptwave.scripting.CWScriptable
      com.conceptwave.scripting.CWCache
          com.conceptwave.scripting.ResourceCache

public class ResourceCache
extends CWCache

Title:

Description: Resources cache The resource cache can store any read-only string data which eventually depends on language. In 6.0 the reference cache functionality was merged in the resource cache which put some limitations on the search type format as follows: Search type = "1" - a language independent resource file resource Search type = "$g" pr "$i" - a Catalog rule source text Search type = metadata name - a visual key of an object - a reference This way the allowed user search types should be strings bigger than 2 characters that do not contain dot character.

getResource

public String getResource(String resourceId,
                          String resourceType,
                          String languageCode,
                          com.conceptwave.scripting.Object expirationTime)
Get string resource from the Resource cache

Parameters:
resourceId - The resource id
resourceType - The resource type. Should be string longer by two characters that does not contain dot character. Violation of this rule may result in unpredictable results or crashes
languageCode - Two or five letter language code. Should match exactly a language code in the application language list. If not specified or null no language code will be stored for the resource. Such resource can be obtained only if the getResource operation does not specify language code. if the parameter has constant value CURRENT_USER_LANGUAGE or the 2 or 5 letter language code is incorrect the language of the current user session will be used
expirationTime - An optional expiration parameter which is used to set the expiration time of the cached object in the case it does not exist in the memory and will be returned from the cache loader. Can be a numeric value specifying the interval in seconds the object is valid starting at the current moment or a date object which specifies the exact moment the object will expire. If not specified or null null the expiration interval set by the loader will be used and if the loader does not set expiration time the object will never expire. Negative expiration intervals are treated as zero intervals - i.e. the object expires immediately.
Returns:
The resource text or null if the resource does not exist
